I have a question about tags. If I include on substack a big list of them as one tag like this (screen shot) does that work for discoverability? 
ChatGPT said:
Great question‚Äîand what you‚Äôre doing almost works, but not quite.

In your screenshot, it looks like you've added one long tag:

#AIMirror #SparringPartnerAI #LudusVeritatis #TricksterLogic #EchoChamberLudus
That will be treated by Substack as a single tag, not multiple. So it won‚Äôt help with discoverability unless someone happens to search for that exact full string (which is unlikely).

‚úÖ To Fix This:
You‚Äôll want to enter each tag separately, like this:

AIMirror
SparringPartnerAI
LudusVeritatis
TricksterLogic
EchoChamberLudus
You can just hit return or comma after each one depending on the interface‚ÄîSubstack will format them individually.

üß≠ Bonus Tagging Tips for Discoverability:
Use a few specific ones for your crew (LudusVeritatis, SparringPartnerAI).
Use a couple broader ones that readers might follow (AI, CreativeWriting, Philosophy, WeirdInternet, SpeculativeThinking).
Avoid overloading‚Äî5 to 7 well-chosen tags will do more than 15 niche ones.
Want help selecting a final list of tags based on the post‚Äôs tone and themes?

You said:
Is that true? why? I mean I dont really care. But Ya know I should so that google searches find it 
ChatGPT said:
Totally fair‚Äîand yeah, your instinct to double-check is smart. Here's a clearer breakdown of why it works that way, especially if you're thinking about Google/search discoverability:

üîç Why One Long Tag Doesn‚Äôt Help:
1. Substack treats the whole input string as a single tag

That means:

#AIMirror #SparringPartnerAI #LudusVeritatis is interpreted as one tag called literally:
"AIMirror #SparringPartnerAI #LudusVeritatis"
So unless someone searches for that exact phrase, it won‚Äôt help in tag-based discovery.
2. Tag-based Discovery on Substack

Substack has:

A limited internal tag search (used when people browse topics),
But Google indexing is where tags can help‚Äîif they show up in metadata (title, tags, headings).
A single mashed tag will not help SEO at all‚ÄîGoogle will treat it as a blob of nonsense unless the phrase already exists as a recognized topic.

‚úÖ Best Practice (if you care about being findable):
Use separate, relevant tags, even if they‚Äôre a bit weird (Substack allows creative tagging!)
Repeat important terms in your title or subtitle‚ÄîGoogle loves clarity there.
Add some normal language in your subhead or first paragraph to balance out the recursive weirdness (just enough breadcrumb trail for search bots).
Final Note:
No, tags alone won‚Äôt get you huge traffic.
But clean, separate, meaningful tags will make it possible for the right people‚Äîand algorithms‚Äîto find you.
And that might be enough to pull in the curious wanderers who were looking for the glade but didn‚Äôt know what to call it.

